        "email": "andrew.perepechko@hpe.com",
        "username": "panda"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-12 14:00:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThe explanation in the commit message looks wrong. There's no need to synchronize the @event variable between event=1; wake_up(...); and wait_event(..., event==1);",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "ba6064de16201898bb05f069b448f49893e9a6c4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-03-12 21:28:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThis was landed before the patch was landed upstream so my explanation is clucky. The upstream commit had this:\n\nlustre: statahead: missing barrier before wake_up\n    \nA barrier is missing before wake_up() in ll_statahead_interpret(),\nwhich may cause 'ls' hang. Under the right conditions a basic 'ls'\ncan fail. The debug logs show:\n    \nstatahead.c:683:ll_statahead_interpret()) sa_entry software rc -13\nstatahead.c:1666:ll_statahead()) revalidate statahead software: -11.\n    \nObviously statahead failure didn't notify 'ls' process in time.\nThe mi_cbdata can be stale so add a barrier before calling\nwake_up().\n    \nneilb: change to use smp_store_release() in a more appropriate\nlocation, and a matching smp_load_acquire().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    }
  ],
